<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-603-961  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 603 961.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Communications  Sept 1990 v13 n7 p387(12).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Algorithm for the p(subscript i)-persistent protocol forhigh-speed fibre optic networks.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mukherjee, Biswanath.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The p(subscript i)-persistent protocol has been proposed forpacket-switched, multiple access communication over high-speed,fibre optic (unidirectional) bus networks.andP;  In this paper thisprotocol is further developed in order to make it easilyimplementable by allowing it to be sensitive to variations in theoffered traffic; in so doing, the protocol's infinite buffer modelis studied.andP;  The corresponding conditions for channel stabilityare first obtained.andP;  Two criteria for fairness in selection of thep(subscript i) are examined, based on equal average packet delayand equal average effective service time for all stations.andP;  It isfound that, even with infinite buffers, this protocol can achievea channel capacity of unity, it provides good delay againstthroughput behaviour, and it is insensitive to the bus length anddata rate.andP;  Simulation results which verify the analytical modelm are also included.andP;  Finally, for implementing the p(subscripti)-persistent protocol, a simple distributed algorithm is providedusing stations which can properly adjust their p(subscript i) whenthe network loading fluctuates.andP;  (Reprinted by permission of thepublisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsBusesNetworksCommunicationProtocolAlgorithmsModelingPerformanceFeedback.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   SUBS network performance with improper p/subscript i. (table)DUBS network performance; equal average packet delay fairnesscriterion. (table)DUBS network performance; equal average effective service timecriterion. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>